<span id="fn_729"></span>[269:4](sbe1926.htm#fr_729.md) These and the
succeeding comparisons represent the condition of Ânanda in prospect of
Buddha's death.

<span id="fn_730"></span>[270:1](sbe1926.htm#fr_730.md) That is, the eye of
Buddha, about which so much is said in the books.

<span id="fn_731"></span>[270:2](sbe1926.htm#fr_731.md) Such appears to be
the meaning of the passage, implying that the disappearance of darkness
is but for a moment.

<span id="fn_732"></span>[270:3](sbe1926.htm#fr_732.md) Or, alas! why bring
it out!

<span id="fn_733"></span>[270:4](sbe1926.htm#fr_733.md) The expression
here, as in other cases, is a strong affirmative, 'the true law of
truth,' 'the only true law;' the word 'law' means religious system.

<span id="fn_734"></span>[271:1](sbe1926.htm#fr_734) '(The character of.md)
self-nature,' or as in the text.

<span id="fn_735"></span>[271:2](sbe1926.htm#fr_735.md) 'All things that
have a personal or individual existence.' It would be well to compare
the, spirit of this sermon with the old belief of the Veda, respecting
the birth of the 'one nature' from which the visible world took shape
(History of Ancient Sanskrit Literature by Max Müller, p. 561). It seems
that the effort of Buddha was to transcend the time of the birth of this
nature, and thus arrive at the condition of the original first cause,
which 'breathed breathless;' in other words, this is the condition of
Nirvâ*n*a.

<span id="fn_736"></span>[271:3](sbe1926.htm#fr_736.md) As in the
concluding verse of the Va*g*ra*kkh*edikâ Sûtra, 'târakâ timira*m*,' &c.
Analecta Oxoniensia, Aryan Series, vol. I, part i, p. 46.

<span id="fn_737"></span>[271:4](sbe1926.htm#fr_737.md) 'Love' in the sense
of parental love; or the love which produced the world.

<span id="fn_738"></span>[271:5](sbe1926.htm#fr_738.md) In the Rig-veda
(according to Dr. Muir) the gods though spoken of as immortal are not
regarded as unbeginning or self-existent; see Journal of the Royal
Asiatic Society, 1864, p. 62.

<span id="fn_739"></span>[271:6](sbe1926.htm#fr_739.md) That is, there
would be no need to seek salvation, for it would be already possessed.

<span id="fn_740"></span>[272:1](sbe1926.htm#fr_740.md) The 'body of the
law' represents the teaching of the word of Buddha, which teaching is
supposed to be accompanied with or attended by a living power, ever
dwelling with the congregation of the faithful.

<span id="fn_741"></span>[272:2](sbe1926.htm#fr_741.md) 'That which is
wanting only resides in this.'

<span id="fn_742"></span>[272:3](sbe1926.htm#fr_742.md) The Chinese 'siang'
is equivalent to Sanskrit sa*ñgñ*â, the third skandha (constituents of
personal being). It is the receptive (subjective) power, in distinction
to the perceptive power (vedanâ). Buddha denied the necessity of
personal consciousness (i.e. of self-consciousness, or consciousness of
self) as an element of life, i.e. life in the abstract.

<span id="fn_743"></span>[272:4](sbe1926.htm#fr_743.md) This idea of 'an
island' (dvipa), fixed amid the running stream of life, is found in
Dhammapada, verse 25.

<span id="fn_744"></span>[273:1](sbe1926.htm#fr_744.md) The law of
production, stability, and destruction; this refers to the Buddhist
theory of the successive stages in the development of the world. The
world is produced from chaos, established for a period, and then
destroyed; and this law is a perpetual one, extending through all space
(the infinite systems of worlds) and through all time.

<span id="fn_745"></span>[273:2](sbe1926.htm#fr_745.md) Nirvâ*n*a,
quietness and extinction.

<span id="fn_746"></span>[273:3](sbe1926.htm#fr_746.md) The sa*m*skâras,
the elements of being, i.e. individual being (for a full account of this
