consult Colebrooke, Hindu Philosophy, p. 254, and Burnouf (Introduction,
pp. 504, 505, note 2).

<span id="fn_747"></span>[274:1](sbe1926.htm#fr_747.md) 'Hearing it,' in
the original, i.e. hearing the report of Buddha's approaching death.

<span id="fn_748"></span>[274:2](sbe1926.htm#fr_748.md) 'The right use of
means' is the rendering of the Chinese 'fang pien,' the Sanskrit upâya;
this term may mean 'by artifice,' or, 'by way of expedient;' but
generally it refers to the use of means to an end, where the 'means' are
evanescent and illusory; the end attained, lasting and real.

<span id="fn_749"></span>[274:3](sbe1926.htm#fr_749.md) Here we have the
well-known Pâli formula 'sabbe sa*m*khârâ ani*kk*â.'

<span id="fn_750"></span>[275:1](sbe1926.htm#fr_750.md) That the gods were
